            content: `
              <h3>What is Public Service Ethics?</h3>
              <p>Ethics in public service refers to the set of moral principles, values, and standards that guide the behaviour of government officials. Unlike private sector employees who serve company interests, civil servants serve the public interest. This distinction carries profound ethical obligations. The citizens of Lagos State trust you with their taxes, their data, and their welfare — a trust you must never betray.</p>
              <p>The Code of Conduct Bureau and Tribunal Act establishes the Code of Conduct for Public Officers in Nigeria. Key provisions include: prohibition of corruption and bribery; obligation to declare assets upon assumption of office and annually thereafter; prohibition of maintaining foreign bank accounts; avoidance of conflict of interest; and maintenance of dignity and decorum in official conduct.</p>
              <h3>Anti-Corruption Principles</h3>
              <p>Corruption is defined broadly to include bribery (giving or receiving anything of value to influence official action), embezzlement (misappropriation of public funds), nepotism (favouring relatives in official decisions), and abuse of office (using official position for personal gain). All these acts are criminal offences under the Corrupt Practices and Other Related Offences Act (ICPC Act) and the Economic and Financial Crimes Commission Act (EFCC Act).</p>
              <p>You are required by law to report any corruption you witness or become aware of. Whistle-blower protections exist to shield civil servants who report corruption in good faith. The Lagos State Government also operates a dedicated ethics helpline. Remember: staying silent when you witness corruption makes you complicit in it.</p>
              <h3>Practical Ethics in Daily Work</h3>
              <p>Ethical conduct is not abstract — it manifests in daily decisions. Arriving at work on time is an ethical act (you are paid for those hours). Processing a file promptly without demanding gratification is ethical. Treating all members of the public with equal respect regardless of their status is ethical. Protecting confidential government information is ethical. In every interaction and every decision, ask yourself: "Would I be comfortable if my supervisor, the public, or the press could see exactly what I am doing and why?" If the answer is yes, proceed. If not, reconsider.</p>
            `
