            content: `
              <h3>The Constitution as the Supreme Law</h3>
              <p>The 1999 Constitution of the Federal Republic of Nigeria (as amended) is the supreme law of the land. Section 1(3) explicitly states that any law inconsistent with its provisions is void to the extent of the inconsistency. As a senior civil servant, you must understand the constitutional framework within which the Lagos State Government and the civil service operate, because your decisions and actions have legal consequences that must remain within constitutional bounds.</p>
              <p>Nigeria operates a federal system of government with three tiers: the Federal Government, State Governments, and Local Government Areas. The Constitution allocates legislative powers through the Exclusive Legislative List (which only the Federal Government can legislate on), the Concurrent Legislative List (where both Federal and State governments can legislate, with Federal law prevailing in cases of conflict), and the Residual List (where states have exclusive legislative powers). Understanding this division is critical for determining which tier of government has authority over any given matter.</p>
              <h3>Fundamental Rights and Civil Service</h3>
              <p>Chapter IV of the 1999 Constitution guarantees fundamental rights to all persons in Nigeria. As a civil servant, you have a constitutional obligation to uphold these rights in your official conduct. The most relevant include: the right to dignity of human person (Section 34), which prohibits degrading treatment of citizens you serve; the right to fair hearing (Section 36), which applies both to how you treat citizens in administrative processes and to your own disciplinary proceedings; and the right to freedom from discrimination (Section 42), which obliges you to serve all citizens without prejudice.</p>
              <h3>Lagos State and Federalism</h3>
              <p>Lagos State, as a federating unit, has its own Constitution (the Lagos State Constitution) and legislation enacted by the Lagos State House of Assembly. The Lagos State Civil Service Commission derives its authority from Section 197 of the Federal Constitution but operates under the Lagos State Civil Service Commission Law. Key Lagos State laws that directly affect your work include the Lagos State Public Service Rules, the Lagos State Revenue Administration Law, the Lagos State Urban and Regional Planning and Development Law, and the Lagos State Pension Reform Law.</p>
            `
