          questions: [
            { q: "Strategic leadership primarily focuses on:", opts: ["Day-to-day operational efficiency","Direction, culture, and long-term institutional capability","Minimising expenditure","Enforcing rules and regulations"], ans: 1, exp: "Strategic leaders focus on shaping direction, culture, and long-term capability — not just managing current operations." },
            { q: "Which of the following is NOT a criterion for evaluating policy options?", opts: ["Effectiveness","Equity","Personality of the policymaker","Administrative feasibility"], ans: 2, exp: "Policy options are evaluated on effectiveness, efficiency, equity, political feasibility, and administrative feasibility — not personality." },
            { q: "Policy implementation failure is:", opts: ["Less common than design failure","More common than design failure","Equal in frequency to design failure","Not a significant concern in government"], ans: 1, exp: "Research shows policy implementation failure is far more common than design failure in the public sector." },
            { q: "At GL12, a key leadership responsibility is:", opts: ["Doing all technical work personally","Identifying and developing future leaders within your team","Avoiding delegation","Minimising interaction with other MDAs"], ans: 1, exp: "Strategic leaders at GL12 should intentionally identify and develop future leaders, building institutional capacity." },
            { q: "A policy option that is theoretically effective but administratively infeasible is:", opts: ["Still worth trying","Not a realistic policy option","The best type of option","Recommended for future consideration only"], ans: 1, exp: "Administrative feasibility is a real constraint — a policy that government lacks the capacity to implement is not a genuine option." },
            { q: "Involving implementers early in policy design helps to:", opts: ["Increase the budget required","Reduce resistance and improve implementation success","Make the policy more complex","Delay the launch"], ans: 1, exp: "Early involvement of frontline implementers reduces resistance, surfaces practical challenges, and improves implementation success." },
            { q: "A performance culture is BEST established by:", opts: ["Writing detailed performance policies","The leader modelling the behaviour expected of the team","Threatening poor performers with dismissal","Conducting frequent inspections"], ans: 1, exp: "A performance culture starts with the leader — your own conduct, punctuality, and work quality sets the standard for the team." },
            { q: "The 'unintended consequences' of a policy refer to:", opts: ["The intended outcomes","Outcomes that were planned but not achieved","Outcomes that were neither planned nor anticipated","The cost of implementing the policy"], ans: 2, exp: "Unintended consequences are outcomes — often negative — that were neither planned nor anticipated in policy design." },
            { q: "Which of the following is most critical at the start of policy design?", opts: ["Announcing the policy publicly","Identifying who will implement it","Precisely defining and understanding the problem","Calculating the budget"], ans: 2, exp: "Effective policy begins with rigorously defining and understanding the problem — its scope, causes, and affected population." },
            { q: "Delegating operational tasks while maintaining oversight is a feature of:", opts: ["Micromanagement","Strategic leadership","Abdication of responsibility","Technical management"], ans: 1, exp: "Strategic leaders delegate operational work (while maintaining oversight) to free time for strategic thinking and stakeholder management." }
          ]
